    "topic": "How to manage and dealing with fake content on social media.",
    "opinion": "As someone who only checks social media a few times a month, I've seen enough fake content to make my head spin. Living in Naples, working as an electrician part-time, and raising two kids with my husband, I don't have time for nonsense. When I do log on, usually during a quiet moment after the kids are in bed or while I'm knitting, I see all these wild stories - politicians saying crazy things, miracle cures, people winning money from random links. It's exhausting. My husband shows me things sometimes, and I just shake my head. I'm not formally educated like some people, but I've got common sense. My parents only went to primary and lower secondary school, but they taught me to question things. With my depression, seeing all this fake stuff just makes me feel worse about the world. It's like everyone's shouting lies at each other. What I do is simple: I don't share anything unless I'm absolutely sure it's true. If something seems too good to be true, like those 'click here for free money' posts, I ignore it completely. When my friends send me questionable things in messages, I tell them straight - 'That looks fake to me.' I'm not very agreeable according to those personality tests, so I have no problem saying when something smells wrong. My high conscientiousness means I take information seriously. I treat social media like I treat my electrical work - you can't cut corners with safety. One wrong wire and everything goes bad. One shared fake story and you're spreading problems. I focus on my real hobbies instead - birdwatching gets me outside in nature, board games with my family keep us connected, knitting lets me create something real with my hands. Those things don't lie to me. Social media should be a tool, not a trap. The companies running these platforms need to do better at stopping fake content before it spreads. But until they do, it's on us regular people to be careful. Check sources, think before sharing, and remember that just because something's online doesn't make it true. My kids are growing up with this stuff everywhere, and I'm teaching them the same - don't believe everything you see, especially from people you don't know personally. It's about protecting your peace of mind in a noisy world.",
    "reasoning_summary": "Derived opinion from persona traits: Limited social media use (few times monthly) suggests perspective comes from occasional observer rather than heavy user. Occupation as electrician implies practical, hands-on approach to problems. No formal education but high conscientiousness suggests reliance on common sense and careful evaluation rather than academic methods. Low agreeableness supports willingness to confront fake content directly. High neuroticism combined with depression indicates emotional impact of encountering misinformation. Hobbies (birdwatching, board games, knitting) suggest preference for real-world, tangible activities over digital spaces. Parental education background implies valuing practical wisdom over formal schooling. Age (27) and having two children indicates concern about misinformation's impact on family. Native-born Italian in Naples provides cultural context of community-oriented skepticism. The opinion emphasizes personal responsibility, skepticism of too-good-to-be-true claims, and prioritizing real-world connections over digital noise, aligning with persona's practical lifestyle and emotional vulnerability to negative content."
